[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction to the Yugoslav"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White prepares to open the center with 3.d4 because he has a lead in development. }
2... d6 { Black prepares ...Nf6 by impeding e5. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ 4...Nc6  5.c4!  White gains space and impedes Black from playing  ...d5  or  ...b5.  This makes White's queenside more exposed, so White should castle kingside, but he should be comfortable with a positional game because he has more space and good control of the  d5  square   4...g6  5.c4  is similar to  4...Nc6 }
5. Nc3 g6
{ Black prepares to fianchetto his kingside bishop which would be very active on the open long diagonal. }
6. Be3
{ If Black's fianchettoed bishop were traded, Black's kingside would have weak dark squares. Therefore, White prepares to trade bishops. His plan is f3  (preventing ...Ng4 and preparing g4)  with Qd2, Bc4  (developing a piece and preventing ...d5)  with O-O-O and at some point Bh6. White also intends on opening the h file to take advantage of Black's kingside weaknesses that would be evident if the dark-squared bishops were traded. }
6... Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 { 7...O-O transposes, it makes no difference. } 8. Qd2 O-O
9. Bc4
{ If White had played 9.0-0-0 instead, Black could strike in the center with ...d5 according to the principle 'counter a flank attack with a counter-attack in the center' and would have a good position. }
9... Bd7
{ Black can play other 9th moves, but they are usually slower and allow White an attack at least as powerful as after 9...Bd7. }
10. O-O-O Rc8
{ Rc8 has an x-ray on the c file on Bc4 and Kc1. Black is threatening ...Nxd4 with an attack on Bc4.   10...Rb8  is an interesting alternative, with a different main method of attacking White's queenside   ...b5-b4 }
11. Bb3
{ This is a sharp position where both sides have clear plans. Black aims to attack White's queenside, where White's king is. Black usually plays ...Ne5-Nc4 to gain the bishop pair, and sometimes sacrifices the exchange with ...Rxc3 in order to expose White's queenside  (if White's queen leaves d2 with a premature Bh6 and ...Bxh6)  . Black's queenside attack is helped by Black's fianchettoed bishop baring pressure down the queenside. White's plan is to open the h file  (g4 with h4 and h5, or sometimes h4-h5 without g4 as a pawn sacrifice)  , trade dark squared bishops, and attack Black's kingside. White's plan is rather straightforward, so it can be very difficult to defend Black's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Yugoslav Attack: Illustrative games"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov vs. Viktor Korchnoi: h4-h5 pawn sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was part of the final section of the Candidates Tournament of 1974. Whoever won this 24 game match was supposed to play Bobby Fischer in the World Championships. Bobby Fischer defaulted, so this 24 game match decided who was the World Champion. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2
O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. h4
{ White aims to pry open the h file at the cost of a pawn. } 10... Rc8
{ Due to games like this which showed the ease in which White could get a powerful attack, masters who played the Dragon began meeting h4 with ...h5, which became mainline.   10...h5  is more accurate, though it has drawbacks too: White can play  (after preparation)  a double pawn sacrifice to open the kingside with g4 ...hxg4 h5. }
11. Bb3 Ne5 12. O-O-O
{ White has transposed into the mainline with 12. h4.   12.h5 !  could have transposed into the game without allowing Black to play ...h5. }
12... Nc4 { 12...h5 ! } 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h5
{ Playing h4-h5 without g4 is usually more effective than g4 first because in these types of positions, attacking speed is very important  (a delay can give Black more chances of generating queenside counterplay)  , and it is worth sacrificing a pawn to open the h file. If Black's attack was slowed by a tempo then g4 before h4 gives White a similar attack without losing a pawn. }
14... Nxh5 { Taking with the pawn exposes Black's kingside too much. } 15. g4
Nf6 16. Nde2
{ Prophylaxis ! White wants to bring his queen into the attack without allowing ...Rxc3  (exposing White's queenside)  so White defends against Black's only source of counterplay before continuing his attack. }
16... Qa5 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 Rfc8 19. Rd3
{ Black has no counterplay due to White's defensive moves Nde2 and Rd3. Now White can finish Black off without having to calculate complex variations Where Black gets counterplay. }
19... R4c5
{ Supposedly defending against White's threat of g5. But this is too slow - White can play it anyways. This is Black's only mistake this game   except for not playing the accurate  10...h5  or  12...h5  but it was enough to lose.   19...Qd8  is stronger, but White still has a huge attack on the h file and can play 20. g5 Nh5 21. Nf4   20.Nd5  is another strong way to continue the attack  White is significantly better but is probably not winning because in some lines Black can give back the pawn  (and get a worse pawn structure)  with ...Qf8 trading queens. }
20. g5 { Sacrificing a pawn. } 20... Rxg5
{ 20...Nh5  21.Nf4  Gives White a winning attack. } 21. Rd5 Rxd5 22. Nxd5
{ Preparing to remove the defender of the h7 pawn with Nxf6+. } 22... Re8
{ 22...Nxd5  23.Qxh7+  Kf8  24.Qh8# } 23. Nef4
{ Preparing to Nxf6+ followed by Qxh7+ and Nd5  (cutting off Black's escape square on e7)  before or after Qh8+ }
23... Bc6 24. e5
{ An interference tactic - preventing Black's queen from guarding the 5th rank. }
24... Bxd5 { 24...dxe5  25.Nxf6+  exf6  26.Nh5  gives White a winning attack. }
25. exf6 exf6 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. Qh8+
{ Black resigns. 27... Ke7 28. Nxd5+ Qxd5 29. Re1+ wins Black's rook or queen. }
