[Black "Viswanathan Anand vs. Kiril Georgiev: Double pawn sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in 1997. Black was a Grandmaster rated 2670. } 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9.
Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Na5 11. Be2
{ Bb3 allows ...Nxb3. White is likely to transpose into the main lines after ...Rc8 and ...Nc4. }
11... Rc8 12. Kb1
{ A useful prophylactic move, getting off of the c1-h6 diagonal  (checks can sometimes happen here after trades if White's king was on c1)  and defends the a2 pawn which can be useful if Black later plays ...Qa5 with ...Rxc3. }
12... a6
{ Too slow. This gives White enough time to spend a tempo on g4  (h4 can be played without a pawn sacrifice)  .   12...Nc4  13.Bxc4  Rxc4  with either g4 or h4 next. }
13. g4
{ White can afford to play g4 due to Black's lost time on a6. Sometimes g4 gives Black counterplay by allowing ...b5 without being prepared by ...a6 as taking on b5 can be met with the deflective ...Nxf3 Nxf3 ...Bxb5. However, for this to work, Black's knight must be on e5, and White's light-squared bishop on b3  (or a square that doesn't guard f3)  . Here it wouldn't matter anyway, as Black lost a tempo with ...a6. }
13... b5 14. h4 e6 { Preventing Nd5 after ...b4 } 15. a3 { preventing ...b4 }
15... h5
{ If Black allows h4-h5 without White sacrificing a pawn, then White would have a powerful attack for no compensation. }
16. Bg5
{ Pinning Nf6. White intends to take on h5 next in order to open the g file. }
16... hxg4 17. h5
{ A thematic double pawn sacrifice. White can usually win at least one of the pawns back and opening the kingside accelerates White's attack. }
17... gxh5 18. Rxh5
{ White's attack is desicive. 18. fxg4 or 18. Bh6 were also good ways of continuing the attack. }
18... Rc5 19. fxg4 Rxc3
{ Black is desperate for counterplay. If Black just waits, White's attack on the kingside will quickly win. }
20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Qxc3 { Now White has a material advantage and the attack. }
21... Nc4 22. Bxc4 bxc4 23. Qxc4 Rc8 24. Qxa6 Qe7 25. Rh3 Bf6 26. Rb3 Be5 27.
Nf3 Bf4 28. Rb4 d5 29. exd5 Qc5 30. c3 *

