[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Sidelines before move 11"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: Why not 9.0-0-0?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O
{ This is a common move nowadays because it avoids a lot of mainline theory. 9.0-0-0 is also a logical move because if Black follows the plan that is normal against 9.Bc4   ...Bd7  ...Rc8  ...Ne5  ...Nc4  then when White's light-squared bishop is traded White saved 2 tempi on moving Bf1 that he can use to speed up his kingside attack. 9.Bc4 is objectively stronger because it prevents Black's next move. }
9... d5 { The center opens up and Black has good counterplay. } 10. exd5
{ 10.Qe1  e5! } 10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ 12.Nxd5  exd5  13.Qxd5  Qc7  14.Qxa8  Bf5  15.Qxf8+  Kxf8  gives Black a powerful initiative with more than enough compensation for the sacrificed material. }
12... Bxd4
{ 12...e5  13.Bc5  Be6!  is also theory, with excellent compensation for the exchange }
13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ The position is rather dry and the endgame that soon follows is around equal. }
