1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Nxd4
{ Black intends on following up with ...Be6 but ...Nxd4 improves White's center control. }
10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Bb3
{ Bobby Fischer's choice. See Fischer vs Larsen  (Yugoslav Attack: Illustrative games chapter) }
11... Qa5 { The most common move. Black intends to follow up with ...Rfc8. }
12. O-O-O b5 { An interesting alternative to 12...Rfc8. } 13. Kb1
{ Useful Prophylaxis. White is provoking ...b4. Sometimes Nd5 becomes threatening. Nd5 centralizes and has a discovered attack on Qa5 with potential in between moves  (Nxf6+ or Nxe7+)  if Black trades queens with ...Qxd2. }
13... b4
{ If Black does not play this, he has no way to fight for the initiative. } 14.
Nd5 Bxd5 { 14...Nxd5  15.exd5  Bd7  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Rhe1  is similar } 15.
exd5 Qb5 { Preparing ...a5. } 16. Rhe1 a5 17. Qe2
{ White is playing for pressure down the e file and is better in the resulting endgame. }
