[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Sidelines before move 11"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: 9...Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Nxd4
{ Black intends on following up with ...♗e6 but ...♘xd4 improves White's center control. }
10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Bb3
{ Fischer's choice. See Fischer vs Larsen  (in the Yugoslav Attack: Illustrative games chapter) }
11... Qa5 { The most common move. Black intends to follow up with ...Rfc8. }
12. O-O-O Rfc8 { 12...Rac8 is similar. } 13. Kb1 b5 14. Rhe1
{ White is centralizing all of his pieces. Due to ...Nxd4 which improved White's center control, White is aiming for central domination. }
14... Bxb3 { 14...b4 is met with 15. Nd5 } 15. cxb3
{ Strengthening the queenside. This reduces Black's attacking potential. White is threatening Bxf6 followed by Nd5 and Nxf6+ damaging Black's pawn structure. }
15... b4
{ The only way to fight for the initiative. White was threatening Bxf6 followed by Nd5. After the trade of queens, White is slightly better because of his more active pieces, superior minor piece, and threats of Nxf6  (damaging Black's pawn structure)  and Nb6  (winning the exchange)  . }
16. Bxf6 { The most forcing continuation. 16. Nd5 is also at least equal. }
16... bxc3
{ 16...Bxf6  17.Nd5  gives White a dominating knight, multiple threats  (Nxf6+ or Qxb4)  (and potential for a kingside attack)  (f4-f5)  (while Black has no counterplay.) }
17. Bxc3 Bxc3 18. bxc3
{ White is slightly better in this endgame because of his queenside pawn majority. This could turn into an outside passed pawn  (if White trades a pair of queenside pawns)  which would give White a won King and Pawn endgame.   18...Qxc3  19.Qxc3   18...Rxc3  19.Re3 }
*

