1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Nd7
{ 9...Nd7 is another sideline which tries to deviate from mainline theory. The idea is to play ...Nb6 or ...Nde5 and try to control the c4 square with both knights. This plan is very slow. If Black wants to attempt to fight for the initiative, he should be rapidly developing his pieces instead of retreating or making slow moves. White can play his normal plan of 0-0-0 with h4-h5. White can even play Be2  (Bb3 is still good)  in response to ...Nb6 or ...Nde5 in order to play b3 controlling the c4 square which would negate Black's main point behind 9...Nd7. }
10. O-O-O { With White's normal plan of h4-h5 opening the kingside. } *

