1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Na5 { 11...Ne5 is the main move. } 12. Kb1
{ Useful prophylaxis and preparing 13.h4 h5 14.g4 for concrete reasons.   12...Nc4  is Black's best move but  13.Bxc4  Rxc4  transposes into  11...Ne5  12.Kb1  Nc4   12...Nxb3  13.cxb3!  helps White defend the queenside as he has an extra pawn there and White still has dangerous attacking ideas such as h4-h5  (...h5 can be met with the typical sacrifice g4 ...hxg4 h5)  (. White even has time for the preparatory g4 if he doesn't want to sacrifice a pawn.)   12...a6  is similar to  12...Nxb3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Sidelines before move 11"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: 10...Qa5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Qa5
{ a common sideline. Black intends on playing ...Rfc8 with ...Ne5 and attacking on the half-open c file. }
11. Bb3
{ Useful prophylaxis: White removes the bishop before it is hit. As Black has blocked his a pawn, he has slowed one of his main methods of counterplay. Black's Queen controls the 5th rank, therefore h4-h5 is harder to achieve. With both side's flank pawn storm's impeded, White should focus on strengthening his position, centralizing  (Rhe1 with Bg5 and f4 with e5)  , and playing Nd5 at some point with a more pleasant position due to his superior center control and initiative. }
11... Rfc8
{ Bringing another piece to the queenside and occupying the half-open c file. }
12. Kb1
{ The king is safer off of the half open c file and now White can play Nd5 without ...Qxd2 being check. }
12... Ne5
{ Against other moves White could have played similarily: strengthening White's center control with Bg5 and Rhe1 with ideas of f4-e5 or Nd5. }
13. Bg5
{ The simplest. White doesn't need to take risks with a kingside attack here due to his powerful centralization  (this was enabled by Black's queen blocking his a-pawn, slowing down potential pawn storm counterplay.)  White removes the bishop from the e file before playing Rhe1 and f4 with e5. White also has the option of Bxf6 followed by Nd5 and Nxf6+ to damage Black's pawn structure  (Nd5 has a discovered attack on Qa5) }
13... Nc4
{ The most common try. ...b5-b4 isn't threatening, it just forces White's knight to go to d5  (it wanted to go there anyway)  .   13...Rc5  intending  Rfc8  is too slow. White has a variety of good options:  14.Bxf6  followed by  Nd5  gives White a slightly better endgame. If White wants to fight for a middlegame initiative he can play  14.h4  or  14.f4  followed by  e5  (before or after Rhe1)  (.) }
14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Nb3
{ 15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nd5  Qxd2  17.Nxf6+  Kg7 !  18.Nh5+  Kh6  19.Rxd2  gives White a slightly better endgame where Black has no counterplay, but  15.Nb3  more or less refutes Black's setup. }
15... Qe5
{ 15...Qd8  loses material by force:  16.e5 !  and  dxe5  loses a piece to  17.Bxf6  followed by  18.Qxd7.  Common theme:  Bd7  can be exposed after e4-e5, especially if White can trade  Nf6. }
16. Rhe1
{ Increasing White's control. White threatens to get a dangerous initiative with f4 followed by e5 and Nd5. One of the main reasons that White's central plan is so effective here  (other than Black's pawn storm being impeded)  is that ...Qa5 undefended Bd7, making f4-e5 plans stronger. }
16... Rxc3
{ Black's only method of counterplay, removing Nc3 before it gets to d5. Black's only compensation is damaging White's queenside pawn structure. Due to White's powerful centralization, Black's compensation for the sacrificed exchange is insufficient. }
17. bxc3
{ Black has insufficient compensation for the sacrificed exchange. White can follow up with Be3-Bd4 and open the center  (increasing the mobility of White's centralized pieces)  with e5. }
