[White "4. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Ne5"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: The punishment for a premature g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5
{ The main move. Black intends to play ...Nc4. } 12. g4
{ g4 preparing h4-h5 is usually good when Black does not have a knight on e5, but with Black's knight on e5 there is a critical difference. With Black's knight on e5, White's main attacking idea is h4-h5  (usually after the prophylactic Kb1)  and can respond to ...h5 with g4 ...hxg4 h5. }
12... b5 13. g5 b4
{ Black has the initiative and is at least equal.   13.Ncxb5  Nxf3!  14.Nxf3  Bxb5  Black has the bishop pair and the initiative. If Black had already traded  Bb3  for  Ne5  with  ...Nc4  , then White could have safely taken on  b5.   13.h4  b4  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.Bxd5  e6  16.Bb3  a5  gives Black a decisive initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Ne5"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: Why not 12.h4 h5 13.g4 with 15.Bh6?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5
{ The main line. Black intends on following up with 12...Nc4. } 12. h4
{ The old mainline, intending on following up with 13.h5. Black players eventually came up with a convincing reply. }
12... h5
{ The main drawback of this move is it allows g4 ...hxg4 h5. Playing this immediately is not very effective for concrete reasons. }
13. g4
{ Due to this being effectively countered, theory moved on to try to prepare this move with Bg5 and Kb1. }
13... hxg4 14. h5 Nxh5 15. Bh6 { 15.Rhg1 is the main alternative. } 15... e6
16. Rdg1 Qf6 17. Bxg7
{ 17.fxg4 allows Black to trade queens: 17...Bxh6 18.Qxh6 Qf4+. This would not have been possible if White's king was on b1. }
17... Qxg7 18. fxg4 Nf6 19. g5 Nh5 20. Nce2
{ White intends Ng3 and has full compensation for the pawn, but Black has an extra tempo to attack compared to the lines with 12.Kb1 Re8 13.h4  (Black's resources include ...Rc5 with ...Rfc8 and ...a5-a4)  as White should play Kb1 soon here because it is far safer on b1. It is better to play Kb1 earlier  (move 12)  because Black doesn't have as useful of a waiting move - Kb1 is useful in lines because it is safer there - and White can choose his attacking plan based on what Black plays. If Black plays a slow move or a move that would not be useful in this position, then White should play 13.h4 h5 14.g4 with a powerful attack. }
