1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5
{ The main line. Black intends on following up with 12...Nc4. } 12. h4
{ The old mainline, intending on following up with 13.h5. Black players eventually came up with a convincing reply. }
12... h5
{ The main drawback of this move is it allows g4 ...hxg4 h5. Playing this immediately is not very effective for concrete reasons. }
13. g4
{ Due to this being effectively countered, theory moved on to try to prepare this move with Bg5 and Kb1. }
13... hxg4 14. h5 Nxh5 15. Rdg1
{ This would be a great move   though  15.Bh6  is stronger because it forces Black to make a decision with his main defender of the kingside, and White can react accordingly  if White's king was on b1. Here this gives Black a great position for concrete reasons. }
15... Rxc3 16. bxc3 { 16.Qxc3  Nxf3 } 16... Qc7
{ Black has time to play 17...Rc8 with an excellent position. Black has 2 pawns for the exchange and will either trade queens after ...Qxc3 or get a queenside initiative.   17.Bh6  doesn't work because of  17...Bxh6  18.Qxh6  Qxc3  with a double threat of  19...Qa1+  20.Kd2  Nxf3+  and  19...Qxd4  , winning a knight. The threat of  ...Qa1+  wouldn't exist if White's king was on  b1  , another clear example of  Kb1  preventing many of Black's resources from being threatening.  17.Bh6  would give White a powerful attack if  Kb1  was played, but here it just loses a knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Ne5"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: Black's equalizer against 12.h4 h5 13.Kb1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4
{ The old mainline, intending on following up with 13.h5. Black players eventually came up with a convincing reply. }
12... h5 13. Kb1
{ 13.Bh6  Bxh6  14.Qxh6  Rxc3  gives Black good counterplay.  After realizing that Bh6 offered Black dangerous counterplay, White turned to the prophylactic Kb1. He intends on choosing an attacking plan depending on what Black plays. }
13... Nc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ This sort of position would be better for white if he had played g4 instead of h4. However, g4  (before h4 ...h5)  is inaccurate with Black's knight on e5 due to ...b5  (White can't take on b5 due to ...Nxf3, a common deflection tactic)  . Therefore, if White was aiming to get this sort of position, he should have played 12.Kb1 first so that he could play g4 after 12...Nc4 13.Bxc4 Rxc4. }
15. Nde2 { 15.Bh6 loses to 15...Rxd4. } 15... b5 16. Bh6 Qa5
{ Black has excellent counterplay. } 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nf4 Rfc8 19. Ncd5 Qxd2
{ 19...b4 keeps the queens on the board with an unclear position. } 20. Rxd2
{ This endgame is equal but Black won in Anand vs Kasparov  (1995, World Championships, 11th game)  . This equalizer was shown in Garry Kasparov's book 'Revolution in the 70s'. }
*

