1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4 h5 13. Bg5
{ The main move. White occupy's an important square, which was weakened by ...h5. Having the bishop on g5 also strengthens specific attacking methods  (such as g4 ...hxg4 f4)  . }
13... Rc5
{ 13...Nh7?!  14.Bh6!  Black's exchange sacrifice with  14...Bxh6  15.Qxh6  Rxc3  isn't as effective with  Nh7  poorly placed. White can play  16.bxc3  followed by  Kb1!  followed by  Ne2  and  f4  where Black has insufficient compensation for the sacrificed exchange.  Black exploits Be3's departure. Rc5 controls the 5th rank, preparing ..b5 and ...a5, and Black sometimes prepares the sacrifice of the exchange after Nd5  (Nd5 is a common attacking theme after White plays the double pawn sacrifice g4 ...hxg4 h5.) }
14. f4
{ A natural move to try to fight for the initiative. White prepares e5. } 14...
Nc4 15. Qd3 Ng4
{ 15...b5  16.e5  is dangerous for Black in most variations, but  16...Ng4  should give Black dynamic equality. }
16. Bxc4 Nf2 17. Qe2 Nxh1 18. Bb3
{ The position is very dynamic but from the objective point of view, Black should be at least equal.   18...Bg4  19.Nf3  Rxc3  20.bxc3  Qa5  21.Rxh1  Qxc3  22.Qd1  a5!  is dangerous for White even though he is up a piece  (Kasparov)   18...Qb6  19.Nf3  Rxg5  20.hxg5  Bxc3  gives Black good counterplay. }
