Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4 h5 13. Bg5
{ The main move. White occupy's an important square, which was weakened by ...h5. Having the bishop on g5 also strengthens specific attacking methods  (such as g4 ...hxg4 f4)  . }
13... Rc5 14. Rhe1
{ Karpov's idea. White is preparing play in the center with f4 and e5. } 14...
b5 15. f4 Nc4 16. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ 16...bxc4? 17.Bxf6 followed by 18.e5 and 19.e6 gives White a positional initiative - Black's light squares are weak.  Karpov vs Sonosko, 1979  This is not a pawn sacrifice as Black can win the e4 pawn if White tries to win the b5 pawn. }
17. e5
{ 17.Bxf6  Bxf8  18.e5  Bg7  is futile for White because  19.e6  is prevented by the pressure on the  d4  knight. }
17... b4 18. Qd3 { 18.exf6  bxc3  19.Qd3  Rxd4  20.Qxd4  exf6  transposes. }
18... Rxd4 19. Qxd4 bxc3 20. exf6 exf6
{ 20...cxb2+  21.Kb1  increases White's king safety because  ...Qa5  doesn't threaten the  a2  pawn. }
21. Qxd6 fxg5 22. Qxd7 Qa5 23. Re8
{ With dynamic equality.  Rowley vs Kudrin, 1981 } *

