1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4 h5 13. Bg5 Rc5 14. g4
{ This should give white an improved version of the 13.g4 line because White prepared g4 with 12.Bg5. }
14... hxg4 15. f4
{ The usual attacking idea with  15.h5  Nxh5  with ideas of  Bh6  and  Rdg1  doesn't work here as  Bh6  loses a tempo and  ...Rc5  was a useful move, so to continue the attack White should try  16.Nd5  but Black can sacrifice the exchange with  16...Rxd5  17.Bxd5  Qb6  attacking the  b2  pawn. Black has 2 pawns for the exchange and has effectively countered White's initiative. }
15... Nc4 16. Qe2 b5
{ This position is dynamically balanced. White's best move here is 17.f5.   16...Qc8  is also possible and threatens  ...Nxb2  but it can be hard for Black to defend after  17.Bxf6  Bxf6  18.Nd5   18.Bxc4  Rxc4  19.Nd5  Re8!  Rxd5!  (the easiest defense from the human point of view)  19.exd5  b5  20.h5 }
