[White "4. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Ne5"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: Black's equalizer against 12.h4 h5 13.Bg5 Rc5 14.Kb1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. h4 h5 13. Bg5 Rc5 14. Kb1
{ 'Today the modern main continuation is 14.Kb1 - an important prophylactic move, reducing the future effectiveness of Black's queenside efforts. It can be called 'advanced prophylaxis': in this way the threats of the opponent, which are as yet not even evident, are neutralized! In addition, it is useful to play the king to b1, whereas for Black there is no such move. White's further actions depend on his reply.' - Kasparov }
14... b5
{ if Black loses time with  14...Re8  (a form of prophylaxis by guarding the e7 pawn in case of Nd5 to free Qd8 to be able to help attack White's queenside)  , then White has time to play  15.Bh6  with a powerful initiative and if Black avoids the trade of bishops with  15...Bh8  then the position is ripe for the thematic double pawn sacrifice  16.g4  hxg4  17.h5 }
15. g4 a5 16. Bxf6
{ 16.gxh5  a4   16...Nxh5  17.Nd5  is dangerous for Black  17.h6+  Bh8  18.h7+  Nxh7  19.Bd5  makes Black defend accurately, though if he finds several accurate moves he should emerge with a slight advantage:  19...b4  20.Nce2  Nxg5  21.hxg5  Bg7!  (preventing the dangerous rook sacrifice on h8. A common theme: White often has dangerous attacking potential on the h file even if the position is objectively equal.)  22.Nf4  Re8!  preparing  ...e6.   21...e6  would allow a dangerous knight sacrifice on  e6.  (White is more or less forced to sac)  (either knight to e6)  (with almost enough compensation)  (from the practical point of view very dangerous)  (but if Black finds several only moves)   23.Nfe6  fxe6  24.Nxe6  Rxd5!  25.Qxd5  Qa8!  (he should emerge to a slightly better endgame. Conclusion: White has lots of dangerous attacking options even in some lines that are inaccurate.) }
16... Bxf6 17. gxh5 a4
{ 18.Bd5 or 18.hxg6 gives White good play for the sacrificed material, though objectively Black should be able to equalize. Conclusion: in the 12.h4 h5 lines, 13.Bg5 Rc5 14.Kb1 is the most dangerous option for White. Objectively Black should be able to equalize, but his task is not enviable as White has many dangerous options to fight for the initiative. However, White can get an even stronger attack with 12.Kb1. }
