[Black "White vs Dragon: 12.Kb1 Nc4 with 15...Rc8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. Kb1
{ Improving White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's dangerous attacking options  (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5)  (or ...Qc7)  (with ...Qxc3 doesn't threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1)  are less powerful. Now Black has to make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. Kb1. }
12... Nc4
{ The most straightforward method of attack, but the obvious drawback is that the knight leaves the centralized post of e5 before white commits to h4 ...h5. }
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4
{ If Black's knight were still on e5, he would have the powerful resource ...b5! where White can't take on b5 without losing the f3 pawn, giving Black the initiative. }
14... b5
{ Black's only method of fighting for the initiative. Anything else is too slow, white will pry open the h file with h4-h5 and get a rapid kingside attack. }
15. b3
{ Aiming to force Black's rook to retreat before taking the b5 pawn  (reducing Black's compensation)  . }
15... Rc8
{ The main line, but concedes a significant advantage without a fight. 15...b4! is more resilient. }
16. Ndxb5 { White wins a pawn and Black has insufficient compensation. } 16...
Qa5 17. a4 { Supporting Nb5 and preparing Nxa7. } 17... a6
{ White was threatening to take the a7 pawn.   A slow move such as  17...Ra8  gives White a decisive initiative on top of having an extra pawn. For example  18.e5  dxe5  19.g5  wins a piece  (a common idea if Bd7 was undefended by ...Qa5)  (.) }
18. Nd5 { White forces a better endgame. } 18... Qxd2
{ 18...Qd8 ?  19.Bb6  Qe8  20.Nxf6  Bxf6  21.Nc7 } 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Rxd2
{ White has a significant  (probably decisive)  advantage in this endgame and has more than enough material for the knight  (Ne7 will be lost)  after White takes on d7 and possibly g6.   20...Rce8  21.Nxg6+   21.Nxd6  Rxe7  22.Nc4  wins the exchange due to the threat of  Bc5  because  22...Ree8  loses a piece to  23.g5  followed by  21.Nxd6  gives White 4 pawns for the knight   20...axb5  21.Nxc8  Rxc8  22.Rxd6  Bc6  23.axb5  (White was threatening g5 followed by Rxd7)  (gives White 3 pawns and the initiative for the exchange.) }
