[White "4. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Ne5"]
[Black "White vs Dragon: 12.Kb1 Nc4 with 15...b4!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. Kb1
{ Improving White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's dangerous attacking options  (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5)  (or ...Qc7)  (with ...Qxc3 doesn't threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1)  are less powerful. Now Black has to make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. Kb1. }
12... Nc4
{ The most straightforward method of attack, but the obvious drawback is that the knight leaves the centralized post of e5 before white commits to h4 ...h5. }
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4
{ If Black's knight were still on e5, he would have the powerful resource ...b5! where White can't take on b5 without losing the f3 pawn, giving Black the initiative. }
14... b5
{ Black's only method of fighting for the initiative. Anything else is too slow, white will pry open the h file with h4-h5 and get a rapid kingside attack. }
15. b3
{ Aiming to force Black's rook to retreat before taking the b5 pawn  (reducing Black's compensation)  . }
15... b4 16. bxc4 bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qc7
{ Objectively White is better here, but Black has a dangerous plan: ...Rc8 with ...Be6 and sometimes ...d5. White should be prepared for this dangerous plan so that he can claim his objective advantage. }
18. h4 { Trying to force ...h5 before playing g5. } 18... d5
{ An interesting but unsound try for Black which was recomended by GM Peter Nielsen's Fritz Trainer. Black gives up a pawn to try to maneuver his kinght to d6, hitting c4. This is unsound if White's king doesn't move to a1. }
19. g5 Ne8 20. exd5 Nd6 21. c5 Rb8+
{ 21...Nb5  22.Nxb5  Rb8  23.Kc1!  transposes } 22. Kc1
{ 22.Ka1 walks onto a dangerous x-ray  (from Bg7)  . This allows Black to get a perpetual with 22...Nb5 23. Qc4 Nd6.   or a dynamically balanced endgame if White sacrifices his queen with  23.Nxb5  Bxc3+  This would be winning for white due to  Nxc7  if White's king was on  c1  , but Black takes White's queen with check.  24.Nxc3 }
22... Nb5 23. Nxb5 Rxb5 { 23...Bxc3?  24.Nxc7 } 24. Bd4
{ Black can win his sacrificed pawn back but has insufficient compensation for the exchange. White has consolidated his material advantage. }
