[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. Kb1
{ Improving White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's dangerous attacking options  (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5)  (or ...Qc7)  (with ...Qxc3 doesn't threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1)  are less powerful. Now Black has to make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. Kb1. }
12... Nc4
{ The most straightforward method of attack, but the obvious drawback is that the knight leaves the centralized post of e5 before white commits to h4 ...h5. }
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4
{ If Black's knight were still on e5, he would have the powerful resource ...b5! where White can't take on b5 without losing the f3 pawn, giving Black the initiative. }
14... b5
{ Black's only method of fighting for the initiative. Anything else is too slow, white will pry open the h file with h4-h5 and get a rapid kingside attack. }
15. b3
{ Aiming to force Black's rook to retreat before taking the b5 pawn  (reducing Black's compensation)  . }
15... b4 16. bxc4 bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qc7
{ Objectively White is better here, but Black has a dangerous plan: ...Rc8 with ...Be6 and sometimes ...d5. White should be prepared for this dangerous plan so that he can claim his objective advantage. }
18. h4 { Trying to force ...h5 before playing g5. } 18... h5
{ If Black doesn't stop h5 or play actively, White will get to play h5 where Black doesn't even have the initiative as compensation for his sacrificed exchange and pawn. }
19. g5 Nh7
{ 19...Ne8?!  intending  ...d5  and  ...Nd6.  20.Rd3!  Black doesn't have as fast counterplay as  Ne8  impeded Black's kingside rook from entering the game. White should develop  Rh1  (preferably with Rhd1)  (and unpin Qc3, after which he will have a significant material advantage for very little compensation) }
20. Ka1
{ Normally, White would not want to place his king on the long diagonal with Bg7 bearing down on it. However, Since Black did not play ...d5  (with the idea of ...Ne8-Nd6 and potentially ...Nxc4 which controls b2)  , this is safe as White has a clear plan: Rb1 with Bc1-Bb2. Then unpin Qc3, move Nd4, and trade dark-squared bishops. After White achieves this, he is in no danger. If Black's knight could go to c4 it would attack b2 which would interrupt this plan. }
20... Rc8
{ Black's main plan is to attack c4. He can continue the pressure with ...Be6 next. }
21. Rb1 Be6
{ 21...Nf8  intending  ...Ne6  is well met by  22.Rhc1!  Intending  Qd2  followed by  c3. }
22. Bc1 Bxc4
{ The endgame after  Qxc4  23.Qxc4  Rxc4  24.c3!  is much better for White because he has a material advantage and  24...Rxc3  doesn't work because of  25.Nxe6  which attacks  Bg7  and intends  Bb2  next. }
23. Bb2
{ White is safe. To consolidate his material advantage, all White needs to do is unpin Qc3 from Bg7's diagonal, move Nd4, trade bishops, and develop Rh1  (preferably to d1)  . Black does not have a dangerous initiative, White's plan is easily achieved. }
*

