[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. Kb1
{ Improving White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's dangerous attacking options  (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5)  (or ...Qc7)  (with ...Qxc3 doesn't threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1)  are less powerful. Now Black has to make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. Kb1. }
12... Re8
{ Prophylaxis. Black defends the e7 pawn before it is attacked by Nd5 in order to give Black's queen more freedom. However, this move is too slow, and is at best neutral  (it could be argued that the rook would be better placed on f8)  if White plays the double pawn sacrifice 13. h4 h5 14. g4 hxg4 15.h5   which  12.Kb1  was preparing as explained by the informational variations on  12.h4  h5  13.g4 }
13. h4
{ Due to ...Re8 being slow, White's thematic double pawn sacrifice almost wins by force. White gets a superior version of 12.h4 h5 13.g4. }
13... h5 14. g4 hxg4
{ The only consistent move. If Black does not play this White will open the g file with gxh5 without needing to sacrifice a pawn. }
15. h5
{ The consistent follow up. Black must capture the pawn or White will get the same sort of dangerous play without sacrificing the pawn. }
15... Nxh5 16. Bh6 Bf6
{ Avoiding the trade of bishops. 16...e6 intending 17...♕f6 is more common. }
17. Nd5
{ White prepares to trade off Black's dark-squared bishop anyways. White has a dangerous attack and intends on playing Rdg1 with fxg4 and Nxf6+. }
*

