[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Ne5 12. Kb1
{ Improving White's king safety before committing to anything else. Many of Black's dangerous attacking options  (checks on the c1-h6 diagonal, Black's thematic exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3 with ...Qa5)  (or ...Qc7)  (with ...Qxc3 doesn't threaten ...Qa1+ if White's king is on b1)  are less powerful. Now Black has to make a commitment. Black doesn't have any waiting move that is as useful as 12. Kb1. }
12... Re8
{ Prophylaxis. Black defends the e7 pawn before it is attacked by Nd5 in order to give Black's queen more freedom. However, this move is too slow, and is at best neutral  (it could be argued that the rook would be better placed on f8)  if White plays the double pawn sacrifice 13. h4 h5 14. g4 hxg4 15.h5   which  12.Kb1  was preparing as explained by the informational variations on  12.h4  h5  13.g4 }
13. h4
{ Due to ...Re8 being slow, White's thematic double pawn sacrifice almost wins by force. }
13... h5 14. g4 hxg4
{ The only consistant move. If Black does not play this White will open the g file with gxh5 without needing to sacrifice a pawn. }
15. h5
{ The consistant follow up. Black must capture the pawn or White will get the same sort of dangerous play without sacrificing the pawn. }
15... Nxh5 16. Bh6
{ stronger than 16. Rhg1  (which is still dangerous)  because White can respond to the exchange sacrifice Rxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 with a counter exchange sacrifice 18. Rxh5 followed by 19. Rh1. White will usually play Rdg1 anyways, but Bh6 is slightly more accurate because occasionally it might be better for White to do something else  (such as Rxh5 followed by Rh1)  whereas White should always play Bh6 in this type of position in order to trade Black's main defender of the kingside. Summary: Both 16.Rhg1 and 16.Bh6 are strong attacking moves, but 16.Bh6 is more flexible. }
16... Kh7
{ 16...e6 intending 17...♕f6 is more common. 16...Kh7 tries to force White into a decision with Bh6. }
17. Bxg7 { White wanted to trade dark-squared bishops anyways. } 17... Kxg7 18.
fxg4 { 18.Rxh5  gxh5  19.Qg5+  doesn't work due to  19...Ng6. } 18... Bxg4
{ 18...Nxg4?  19.Rxh5!  gives White a decisive attack } 19. Nf5+
{ A thematic sacrifice to open the g file. } 19... Bxf5
{ The best defense, but White is still significantly better.   19...gxf5?  20.Qg5+  Ng6  21.exf5   19...Kg8?  20.Qh6  Black lost a tempo and has to take  Nf5  anyways }
20. exf5 Rh8
{ Defending against the threat of Rxh5. Otherwise, fxg6 with Rxh5 would be desicive. }
21. fxg6
{ White has other moves with more than full compensation for the 2 pawns, but this is the most convincing. White continues to open the position. 21...Nxg6 is forced.   21...fxg6  22.Ne4  followed by  23.Ng5  is decisive  White can easily continue the attack with moves like Rdf1 and Rhg1.  Nd5 is sometimes an idea if Black retreats with ...Nf6  White is down 2 pawns but has at least 3 pawns worth of compensation and the game is likely to end in a decisive attack. }
