{ White adds an attacker to the kingside and prepared to take the g4 pawn. }
17... Qf6
{ Slow moves don't work here.   17...a6  loses by force:  18.fxg4  Nf6  19.Bxg7  Kxg7  20.Qh6+  Kg8  21.Qh8# }
18. fxg4 Bxh6 { Forced. } 19. Qxh6
{ If White's king was on b1 here, ...Qf4+ would trade queens, ending White's attack. 12. Kb1 was far more useful than 12...Re8. }
19... Qg7 20. Qd2 Nf6 21. g5 Nh5 22. Nce2
{ White has a decisive attack. According to chess.com's database, White has won all the games in this position  (11/11)  . White's plan is to trade knights with Ng3, double rooks on the h file, trade queens  (Qf4 with Qf6)  , and checkmate Black on the h file. Black can't stop this without making serious concessions worth more than the pawn White sacrificed. White can either meet ...e5 with Nf5!  (usually a decisive breakthrough)  or Ne2-Nc3-Nd5 with good control of the d5 square. Stockfish doesn't immediately notice that White is winning but eventually realizes that White's attack is decisive. }
*

