[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Nxd4"]
[Black "Topalov Dragon (11...Nxd4): Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4
{ Many Black players didn't like Black's chances in the 11...Ne5 12. Kb1! lines, where White is objectively better, so they tried to find earlier improvements. 11...Nxd4  (the Topalov Dragon)  is the main alternative to 11...Ne5. Black aims to follow up with ...b5. }
12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5
{ As Black's queenside pawn storm was sped up by ...♘xd4, White changes plans. White trades off some of Black's most dangerous pieces and opens the e file before fighting for a kingside initiative. }
13... Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 { Threatening ...a4. } 16. a3
{ Creating an escape square for Bb3. This is the main starting position of the Topalov Dragon. Black can play the pawn sacrifice 16...b4.   Black's main alternatives involve preparing  ...b4  with the aggressive  16...Qb6   or the prophylactic  16...Kg8 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Nxd4"]
[Black "Topalov Dragon (11...Nxd4): Why not 13.Bxa7?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4
{ Many Black players didn't like Black's chances in the 11...Ne5 12. Kb1! lines, where White is objectively better, so they tried to find earlier improvements. 11...Nxd4  (the Topalov Variation)  is the main alternative. Black aims to follow up with ...b5. }
12. Bxd4 b5 13. Bxa7
{ Risky. 13th moves other than 13.♘d5 are at least equal for Black.   13.e5  dxe5  14.♗xe5  ♗c6  is equal   13.h4  a5  is dangerous for White with Black's pawn storm coming so fast. }
13... b4 14. Nd5 { 14.Ne2  Qa5  15.Bd4  Ba4  is dangerous for White } 14...
Nxd5 15. exd5 Qa5 16. Qe3
{ 16.Bd4?!  Rxc2+!  17.Bxc2   17.Kxc2  Bf5+   17.Qxc2  Rc8  17...Qxa2  gives Black full compensation for the rook and White's position is very difficult. }
16... Ba4
{ Black has a powerful initiative. He can play ...♗xb3 and double rooks on the c file with at least enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Nxd4"]
[Black "Topalov Dragon: 16...b4 with 18...Kg8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 16. a3 b4
{ Black's main continuation. Black sacrifices a pawn to open some files on the queenside and gain time attacking White's queen if White takes on b4. Black doesn't have any immidiate threats but if the queenside is opened, Black could rapidly bring pieces to the attack with moves like ...Rc5 with ...Qa8 and ...Rb8. }
17. axb4 axb4 18. h4
{ 18.Qxb4 is also playable. White declines the pawn sacrifice in order to fight for the initiative. White will sometimes take the b4 pawn under more favorable circumstances. Black can fight for the initiative with ...Bf5 and ...Qa5, but White's king can escape to the center and eventually the kingside if needed, while Black's king doesn't have the same sort of escape plan for when White opens the kingside with h5. }
18... Kg8
{ 18...Kg8 is Black's best move. Kg8 is useful in all variations and Black can decide which plan to play depending on White's next move. }
19. h5 { White transposed into the 16...Kg8 variation. } *

