1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 16. a3 Qb6
{ 'This used to be considered too slow, but some coorespondance players have tried to revive it based on some concrete ideas. White must trade suprisingly carefully in the next few moves, but once he sidesteps a couple of small tactical tricks, Black's play becomes increasingly artificial. The first point to mention is that Black's ...b4 advance will usuaully be met by the blocking a3-a4 since Black's queen no longer has access to the e8-square. To get around this difficulty, Black often tries to arrange a queenside breakthrough with ...Rb8, ...a5 and ...b4, which will force a queen exchange while avoiding any problem with his queenside structure in the endgame. As long as we can successfully deal with this idea, we should be able to count on a good position' - GM Parimarjan Negi }
17. Rhe1
{ 17.h4 ?  a4  18.Ba2  Rxc2 !  19.Qxc2   19.Kxc2 ?  Bf5+  (Rc8 favors Black as White's queen is exposed and his pawns are weak.)   17.g4  Rc7  followed by  Rfc8  gives Black good counterplay. }
17... a4 18. Ba2 Rxc2+
{ A common idea which would work if White's e1 rook was on h1. White playing Rhe1 made a big difference, now 18...Rxc2+ loses by force. }
19. Kxc2 Bf5+ 20. Re4 *

