[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 16. a3 Kg8
{ The most flexible move. ...Kg8 is useful in all variations and Black waits for White to commit to a specific move or plan before playing ...b4. }
17. h4
{ Preparing to open the h file.   17.Rhe1  Rc5 !  allows Black to bring more pieces to the queenside before playing  ...b4.  White's plan of h4-h5 is faster as it prepares to open the kingside. }
17... b4 18. axb4 axb4 19. h5 Qa5
{ Black brings a piece to the queenside and threatens ...Qa1 checkmate. } 20.
Qd4
{ White centralizes his queen, defending the b2 pawn in case Black plays ...Qa1+, and gives White's king an escape square on d2. }
20... Bf5 21. Kd2
{ White prepares to fight for a kingside initiative by taking defensive measures against Black's counterplay. White's king evacuates the queenside. It is safe in the center as White has so many centralized pieces. White's king can go to the kingside if needed. }
21... Rc5 { The main move. Black aims to double rooks on the c file. } 22. hxg6
{ Provoking ...Bxg6. Black's Bishop is an important defender of the h7 pawn. Opening the h file lessens the effect of any pressure Black has on the c2 pawn because if Black takes on c2, he removes an important defender of the h7 pawn and helps White open the kingside. }
22... Bxg6
{ 22...fxg6  isn't as strong because the  h7  pawn is weaker. White should play the prophylactic  23.Rc1  to prevent any counterplay and improve his king safety with  24.Ke3.  After this, Black doesn't have much to do and White can chase away  Bf5  with  g4  and fight for a kingside initiative. }
23. Ke3
{ Preventing any tricks envolving a sacrifice on c2 followed by ...b3+ } 23...
Rfc8
{ 23...Qc7  24.Rh4  is similar   23...Qb6  24.Rd2  followed by  Rh4  and  Kf2  also gives White enough time to stabilize his position before fighting for a kingside initiative. }
24. g4
{ Preparing f4-f5. White doesn't need to retreat his king more, it is safe in the center. White has a powerful initiative and can keep improving his position  (Rd2 with Rc1 if needed to guard c2 if Black increases the pressure, White's king can escape to f2 if Black opens the center)  and fight for a kingside initiative with f4-f5.   24...Bxc2  25.Bxc2  Rxc2  26.Qe4  favors White as Black can't protect his  h7  pawn. }
