[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 16. a3 Kg8
{ The most flexible move. ...Kg8 is useful in all variations and Black waits for White to commit to a specific move or plan before playing ...b4. }
17. h4 b4 18. axb4 axb4 19. h5 Bf5
{ The most critical move according to Negi. If White does not take the b4 pawn, ...Bf5 commits less than ...Qa5 because Black might play ...Qc7 instead. }
20. hxg6
{ It is useful to force Black to take with the bishop before taking on b4 because this reduces the effectiveness of Black's pressure on c2.  ...Bxc2 trades an important defender of the h7 pawn }
20... Bxg6
{ Black should always meet hxg6 with Bxg6 in order to defend the h7 pawn. } 21.
Qxb4 { White tries to punish Black for not playing ...Qa5. } 21... Rc5 22. Rh4
{ White can swing his rook to the queenside or double rooks on the h file.   22.Rhe1?  22...Qc7!  Black has a powerful initiative on the c file.  22.Rh4  is better because White can intercept Black's counterplay on the c file with  Rc4. }
22... Qa8 { 22...Qc7  23.Rc4  helps White trade pieces. } 23. Kd2
{ White's king can head to the kingside and White can easily bring pieces to the queenside  (Qa4, Rc4)  to help trade pieces. This benefits White as he has an extra pawn, so trading pieces brings White closer to a favorable endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Theory: 10...Rc8 11.Bb3 Nxd4"]
[Black "Topalov Dragon: 16...Kg8 with 19...Bf5 and 21...Rb8!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. exd5 a5 16. a3 Kg8
{ The most flexible move. ...Kg8 is useful in all variations and Black waits for White to commit to a specific move or plan before playing ...b4. }
17. h4 b4 18. axb4 axb4 19. h5 Bf5
{ The most critical move according to Negi. If White does not take the b4 pawn, ...Bf5 commits less than ...Qa5 because Black might play ...Qc7 instead. }
20. hxg6
{ It is useful to force Black to take with the bishop before taking on b4 because this reduces the effectiveness of Black's pressure on c2.  ...Bxc2 trades an important defender of the h7 pawn }
20... Bxg6
{ Black should always meet hxg6 with Bxg6 in order to defend the h7 pawn. } 21.
Qxb4 { White tries to punish Black for not playing ...Qa5. } 21... Rb8
{ Forcing White's queen to a slightly inferior square. } 22. Qc3
{ 22.Qd4 ?!  runs into  22...e5 !  with the following point:  23.dxe6 ?  Rxb3 !  24.cxb3  Qg5+  25.Rd2   25.f4  Rc8  Ra8  26.exf7+  Bxf7  and White is in serious trouble.   22.Qh4  Qa5  23.Rd4  utilizes a common idea, but after  23...Qa1+  24.Kd2  Qxb2  25.Rg4  Qg7 !  Black manages to defend }
22... Qb6
{ Black activates his queen and prepares to bring his last rook into the game with ...Rfc8. }
23. Rd4
{ A typical way of trying to consolidate. Rd4 blocks the Black Queen's path to f2. Rd4 also prepares Bc4 with b3, which is a common idea to try to hinder Black's queenside counterplay. White intends on playing Kd2 next. }
23... Rfc8 24. Bc4
{ White should avoid the temptation to trade rooks with  24.Rc4  because  24...Rxc4  25.Bxc4  Qf2  is fine for Black.  'Planting the bishop on c4 is a typical way to block the queenside. Now White is ready to improve his position with Kd2  (prefaced by b2-b3 if necessary)  followed by the walking of the king to the kingside - perhaps throwing Re1 somewhere along the way. Black has no obvious targets to attack, and must instead shuffle his pieces around in a way that interferes with White's plans, which is not an easy thing to do when the clock is ticking. If and when the white king reaches safety, White will not only have an extra pawn but also attacking chances with g2-g4 and f3-f4.' - Parimarjan Negi }
24... f6 25. Re1
{ It is stronger to play Re1 before b3 because b3 allows Black to fight for counterplay with ...Ra8-Ra2. White should prepare this with Re1 first  (the c2 pawn is easily defended)  especially since Re1 gains a tempo on the e7 pawn. }
25... Kf7 26. b3 { White is perfectly placed to carry out his plan. } *

