Qxb4 { White tries to punish Black for not playing ...Qa5. } 21... Rb8
{ Forcing White's queen to a slightly inferior square. } 22. Qc3
{ 22.Qd4 ?!  runs into  22...e5 !  with the following point:  23.dxe6 ?  Rxb3 !  24.cxb3  Qg5+  25.Rd2   25.f4  Rc8  Ra8  26.exf7+  Bxf7  and White is in serious trouble.   22.Qh4  Qa5  23.Rd4  utilizes a common idea, but after  Qa1+  24.Kd2  Qxb2  25.Rg4  Qg7 !  Black manages to defend }
22... Qb6
{ Black activates his queen and prepares to bring his last rook into the game with ...Rfc8. }
23. Rd4
{ A typical way of trying to consolidate. Rd4 blocks the Black Queen's path to f2. Rd4 also prepares Bc4 with b3, which is a common idea to try to hinder Black's queenside counterplay. White intends on playing Kd2 next. }
23... Rfc8 24. Bc4
{ White should avoid the temptation to trade rooks with  24.Rc4  because  24...Rxc4  25.Bxc4  Qf2  is fine for Black.  'Planting the bishop on c4 is a typical way to block the queenside. Now White is ready to improve his position with Kd2  (prefaced by b2-b3 if necessary)  followed by the walking of the king to the kingside - perhaps throwing Re1 somewhere along the way. Black has no obvious targets to attack, and must instead shuffle his pieces around in a way that interferes with White's plans, which is not an easy thing to do when the clock is ticking. If and when the white king reaches safety, White will not only have an extra pawn but also attacking chances with g2-g4 and f3-f4.' - Parimarjan Negi }
24... Ra8 25. Kd2 e5
{ A crucial move. If Black continues slowly, White will have a great position. }
26. dxe6 d5 { The only move which does not immidiately lose. } 27. Rxh7
{ To defend this position, Black has to find some computer-generated ideas. ...Bxh7 allows Rg4+ and ...Kxh7 allows Rh4+.   27.exf7+  Kf8  28.b3  Ra2  29.Rd3  is another wild computer line that ends in a draw. }
27... f6 { Blocking the long diagonal. } 28. Rh6 Bf5
{ Black's only move to draw. Black prevents Rg4+ } 29. f4
{ White has alternatives at this point. It is Black who should be careful. }
29... Ra7 { White was threatening 30.Qg3+ } 30. e7 { White prepared Bxd5+ }
30... dxc4 { 30...Rxe7 ?  31.Qg3+  Rg7  32.Bxd5+  wins } 31. g4 Rd7
{ Black's bishop was guarding the kingside.   If Black retreats with  31...Be6  then White has several dangerous attacking ideas such as  32.Rxf6   32.Rg6+   32.f5 }
32. Rxd7 Qf2+ 33. Kc1
{ The game will end in a draw due to perpetual check after 33...Bxd7 34. Rxf6 Qf1+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Chinese Dragon"]
[Black "Chinese Dragon: 13...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rb8
{ The Chinese Dragon. Black intends on playing ...b5 and ...Na5-Nc4. If White takes on c4, Black can open the b file and obtain the bishop pair. }
11. Bb3
{ Black was threatening ...b5.   11.h4  b5  12.Ndxb5  is playable but after  Ne5  followed by  Qa5  , Black gets the initiative }
11... Na5 12. h4
{ 12.Bh6  allows Black to obtain counterplay with  Bxh6  and Black will play  ...e5  at some point.  ...e5  is less favorable for Black with dark squared bishops still on the board, so White should delay  Bh6. }
12... b5 13. Kb1
{ After Black plays ...Nc4 Bxc4 ...bxc4, Black can get counterplay on the b file. Therefore, it is useful to play Kb1  (if given enough time, White should also play Ka1 where white can play Rb1 to defend the b2 pawn)  . White could play Kb1 after 13. h5 but 13. Kb1 is more flexible. }
13... e5
{ ...e5 is an effective idea if White played an early Bh6  (Black trads bishops, then transforms the pawn structure in a way that is more favorable without his dark squared bishop because ...e5 blocks the long diagonal)  but it is not favorable for Black here. 13...Nc4 is stronger. }
14. Nde2 b4
{ Black needs active play to try to justify ...e5. If Black plays slowly, White can take the d6 pawn and fight for the d5 square. }
15. Nd5 Nxb3 16. axb3 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Be6 18. Qxd6 { White won a pawn. } 18...
Qa5 19. h5 { Black's compensation is not enough. } 19... Rfc8 20. hxg6 hxg6 21.
Nc1
{ followed by Nd3 and White can put a minor piece on c5.   The active looking  21...Bf8  can be met by  22.Bg5  Bxd6?  23.Bf6  where Black can't stop  Rh8#. }
*

