[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rb8
{ The Chinese Dragon. Black intends on playing ...b5 and ...Na5-Nc4. If White takes on c4, Black can open the b file and obtain the bishop pair. }
11. Bb3
{ Black was threatening ...b5.   11.h4  b5  12.Ndxb5  is playable but after  Ne5  followed by  Qa5  , Black gets the initiative }
11... Na5 12. h4
{ 12.Bh6  allows Black to obtain counterplay with  Bxh6  and Black will play  ...e5  at some point.  ...e5  is less favorable for Black with dark squared bishops still on the board, so White should delay  Bh6. }
12... b5 13. Kb1 h5
{ Attempting to block the kingside, but allows the thematic double pawn sacrifice. 13...Nc4 is better. }
14. g4 e5
{ 14...hxg4  15.h5  Nxh5  16.fxg4  followed by  17.Rdg1  gives White a powerful kingside attack }
15. Nde2 hxg4 16. Bg5
{ White has a powerful kingside attack worth more than the sacrificed material. White can continue opening the kingside with Ng3 and h5. }
