[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "Maroczy bind: 6.Be3 mainline theory explained"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ The Accelerated Dragon. Black delays ...d6 in the hopes of playing ...d5 in one move. }
5. c4
{ The d5 square is under firm control. 5. c4 exposes the queenside, so White should castle kingside. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3
{ The main alternative to 6.Nc2. White has more piece activity, but Black can trade some minor pieces which usually helps Black because he has less space. Black's methods of counterplay are more well known in the 6.Be3 lines so 6.Nc2 has good practical value. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 d6
{ 7...Ng4  8.Qxg4  Nxd4  9.Qd1  is another line where White has some pressure but Black has a solid position and has eased the pressure caused by White's space advantage by trading a pair of knights. }
8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2
{ White aims to finish his development before starting an attack. White usually plays f3 and aims to consolidate his space advantage or attack on the queenside. Playing f4 early on in the Maroczy bind is usually risky because the e4 pawn can be targeted. }
10... Nxd4 { Trading a pair of knights to prepare ...Bc6. } 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. f3
{ White's center is secure, so White can start a queenside attack. } 12... a5
{ Black prevents b4 and has the positional threat ...a4. ...a4 allows Black to open the a file if White plays b3 and Black can sometimes play ...a3 to provoke weaknesses on the dark squares. }
13. b3 Nd7 { Black aims to trade dark squared bishops. } 14. Be3
{ Avoiding the trade. Usually, in the Dragon, it is good for White to trade dark squared bishops, but in the Maroczy Bind with 6.Be3 White is usually not aiming for a kingside attack and White's dark-squared bishop is his best bishop as Be2 is restricted by White's pawn chains. }
14... Nc5
{ Improving the placement of Black's knight. White's pawn storm plan of a3-b4 is harder because of the pressure on b3 and Black prepares to bring his f8 rook into the game with ...Qb6 and ...Rfc8. }
15. Rab1
{ White aims to put his rooks on the b and c files and eventually prepare a3-b4 with a queenside attack. }
15... Qb6 { Impeding a3 with b4 and preparing ...Rfc8. } 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 17. Rc2
{ Preparing a3 by defending Qd2. White is ready to play a3 followed by b4  (after preparation, such as Bf1 and maybe Qf2)  . }
17... Qd8
{ Black unpins. Black's queen has done its job on the queenside.     17...Qb4  has been tried, aiming to prevent  a3.  18.Qc1  White is able to play  a3  anyways and Black will have to retreat his queen. }
18. Bf1
{ When the position opens up, it is useful to be able to play Qf2. White improves his piece coodination before opening the position with a3 and b4. }
18... h5
{ Black's main plan is ...Kh7 with ...Qh8 with pressure on the central dark squares. Other plans are too slow to effectively counter White's pawn storm. }
19. a3 Kh7 20. b4 axb4 { Opening the a file for Black's a8 rook. } 21. axb4 Ne6
{ White has more space and can play Nd5 but Black has compensation in the form of excellent central dark square control and the a file  (Black can play ...Ra3 followed by ...Rca8)  . White's position is slightly better due to his space advantage but Black also has active play. }
