[White "7. Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "Maroczy bind: 6.Nc2 mainline with 10...a5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ The Accelerated Dragon. Black delays ...d6 in the hopes of playing ...d5 in one move. }
5. c4
{ The d5 square is under firm control. 5. c4 exposes the queenside, so White should castle kingside. }
5... Bg7 6. Nc2
{ Avoiding trades. If you have more space, you should usually avoid trades because trading pieces usually helps give more breathing room to the side with less space  (more space gives you more room to maneuver your pieces)  . White has advanced his pawns further than Black, giving him more room to develop and maneuver his pieces. Nc2 is well placed because it prepares a queenside attack with b4  (after ...Nf6)  and if Black prevents b4 with ...a5, White can play Na3-Nb5 taking advantage of the weak b5 square. }
6... d6 { The most flexible. } 7. Be2 Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7
{ Threatening ...Bxc3  (damaging White's pawn structure)  and preparing ...Nc5. If Black had played a different 9th move  (not threatening ...Bxc3)  White could build up his position with Be3 Qd2 Rad1 Rfe1 and pawn storm the queenside starting with b4. If Black prevents b4 with ...a5, White can move Nc2 to the weak b5 square via a3.   9...Be6  10.Be3 }
10. Bd2
{ White can afford to play defensively as he can eventually untangle and his space advantage will allow him to fight for the initiative. }
10... a5 { Preventing b4 but weakening the b5 square. } 11. Na3 Nc5 12. Nab5
{ The c3 knight is now defended with a piece so now white can play Be3, centralize both rooks and keep improving his position. Black's only freeing move   ...f5  opens lines for White's centralized pieces. }
12... Nd4
{ The main move. Black hopes to get some compensation for his cramped position by centralizing. }
13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Bg7
{ 14...Bxc3  15.bxc3  is very risky for Black as Black's kingside dark squares are weak and White has the bishop pair.  15...Re8  16.Qd4  e5  17.Qe3  and White can play  f4  next to open the position for his bishop pair. The position should be objectively equal but White has easier play as he has the initiative. }
15. Bxg7
{ White has more space and can exchange his bad bishop by playing Bg4. Other than Bg4, White also has the option to increase his central domination with Qd4+ followed by Rad1. }
