[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ The Dragondorf  (a hybrid between the Dragon and the Najdorf)  . Black aims to fight for a queenside initiative with ...b5. Normally ...b5 plans in the Dragon are played without ...a6 as ...a6 is usually too slow because White's kingside attack is likely to strike first. This would likely be true here if Black had castled, but here Black delays castling in order to try to generate queenside counterplay  (if White tries opening the h file, Black's king might not be there)  . However, Black is usually very behind in development so White has a variety of powerful attacking options he could try. }
8. Qd2
{ 8. Bc4 is also playable but is risker because ...b5 comes with tempo. } 8...
Nbd7
{ An early ...b5 can me met with  (other than normal development or g4 which are both usually good)  a4 ! trying to open the queenside. }
9. Bc4
{ White has given Black long enough to make a mistake with an early ...b5  (White could have met it with a4)  . White is okay with Black gaining a tempo. }
9... b5 10. Bb3
{ White can play Bh6 next, forcing the trade of bishops. Black has no initiative. Another possibility is g4-g5 and ...Nh5 can me met with Nce2-Ng3 to open the h file. }
