{ This game was a rapid game played for chess.com's 2017 Pro chess league. } 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 8. Bc4
Nbd7 9. Qd2 b5 10. Bb3 Bb7 11. Bh6
{ The alternate plan to g4-g5 with Nce2-Ng3  (g4-g5 with Nce2-Ng3 is more common if White does not play Bc4)  . }
11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Rc8 13. O-O-O { White has a lead in development. } 13...
Rxc3
{ Black has no other method of obtaining counterplay. If Black does not try to get counterplay with this thematic exchange sacrifice, White would quickly develop all of his pieces  (Rhe1, Nd5, possibly the prophylactic Kb1)  while also having excellent prospects for a kingside attack.  g4 with h4-h5 or g5  . }
14. bxc3 Qc7 15. Kb2 { Black has insufficient compensation for the exchange. }
15... Ne5 16. Rhe1
{ White just needs to consolidate his material advantage. This can be done by centralizing all of White's pieces and defending against Black's threats before fighting for the initiaitve. }
16... Qc5 17. Re3 { 17.a4!  allows White to open the a file for his rook }
17... Kd7 18. Qh3+ Kc7 19. Bxf7
{ Gives Black a tactical opporotunity. White should have tried to consolidate with Qg3 and f4 first. }
19... Kb8
{ Black misses his chance.   19...Bc8!  wins material as  20.Be6  or  20.Ne6  allows  20...Nc4+ }
20. Bb3
{ White is up the exchange and a pawn for insufficient compensation. The rest is a matter of technique. }
20... Rc8 21. Qg3 Nfd7 22. f4 Nc4+ 23. Bxc4 Qxc4 24. Nb3 Nb6 25. Rd4 Qc7 26.
