1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 8. Qd2
Nbd7 9. g4
{ 9. Bc4, 9. Bh6, and 9.O-O-O are also good ways of fighting for the initiative. }
9... b5 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. g5
{ The alternative to Bh6, trading dark-squared bishops. } 11... Nh5 12. Nce2
{ White prepares to open the h file with Ng3   ...Nxg3  hxg3  . This is a thematic follow up to g5 in the Dragondorf. }
12... Nb6 13. Ng3 Nxg3 14. hxg3
{ With the open h file and the Black's exposed queenside, it isn't safe for Black to castle in either direction. }
14... d5 15. Qf2
{ 15. Nb3 is also good, preparing to open the center with exd5.   15.Nb3  dxe4?  16.Qxd8+  with  Bxb6 }
15... Nc4 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Ne2
{ White aims to open the center to attack Black's uncastled king. Black isn't safe on any area of the board. Black aims for queenside counterplay, but it isn't enough. }
17... Qa5 18. Bd4
{ Centralizing. Black's queen alone isn't enough to give Black sufficient counterplay. }
18... e5 { Trading bishops would be equivalent to admitting defeat. } 19. Bb6
Qxa2 20. Nc3 Qa1+ 21. Kd2 Qxb2 22. Rb1 Qa3 23. Bc5
{ Black won 2 pawns but will lose a piece. } 23... Qa5 24. Rxb7 d4
{ White also loses a knight, but Black's queen will be trapped. } 25. Bb4 dxc3+
26. Kxc3 { Material is equal but White has a desicive initiative. } 26... Qd8
